{"parentUuid":"11b41cb6-89aa-458c-8973-54469ac51826","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DhTpHPYxyfCKQmoBPfRyas","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"QLoRA 7B fine-tuning RAM requirements batch size 1 quantized\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"QLoRA Step-by-Step — Fine-Tune a 7B Model on a Laptop\",\"url\":\"https://blogs.utilia.dev/qlora-step-by-step-fine-tune-7b-laptop\"},{\"title\":\"LLM Fine-Tuning Hardware Requirements: VRAM, GPU\",\"url\":\"https://llmhardware.io/guides/llm-fine-tuning-hardware-requirements\"},{\"title\":\"Evolution of meta's llama models and parameter-efficient fine-tuning of large language models: a survey\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.12178\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-tuning LLaMA-7B on ~12GB VRAM with QLoRA, 4-bit quantization · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://gist.github.com/Birch-san/57878c4a27cf34f57d3e861865a7d0a2\"},{\"title\":\"BEACON: A Unified Behavioral-Tactical Framework for Explainable Cybercrime Analysis with Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.06555\"},{\"title\":\"Mistral 7B: QLoRA Fine-tuning + 4-bit (Q4/NF4/INT4) VRAM Usage\",\"url\":\"https://kaitchup.substack.com/p/mistral-7b-recipes-for-fine-tuning\"},{\"title\":\"ShareLoRA: Parameter Efficient and Robust Large Language Model Fine-tuning via Shared Low-Rank Adaptation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.10785\"},{\"title\":\"LQ-LoRA: Low-rank Plus Quantized Matrix Decomposition for Efficient   Language Model Finetuning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2311.12023\"},{\"title\":\"Token-wise Influential Training Data Retrieval for Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2405.11724\"},{\"title\":\"Abstractive summarization from Audio Transcription\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2408.04639\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about QLoRA 7B fine-tuning RAM requirements with batch size 1 and quantization:\n\n## Memory Requirements\n\nA 7B model needs approximately 12 GB VRAM with QLoRA. More specifically, one user reported requiring 11,181 MiB when training on sequence lengths of around 337 tokens, and this can be reduced down to about 10.9GB with memory optimization.\n\n## How QLoRA Achieves These Requirements\n\nQLoRA enables developers to fine-tune models like Llama 2 7B on laptops with as little as 16GB of VRAM by combining quantization with LoRA. By quantizing the base model to 4-bit precision while keeping the LoRA adapters in higher precision, QLoRA reduces memory requirements by up to 75% without significantly impacting model quality.\n\n## Memory Breakdown with Batch Size 1\n\nIn a 7 billion parameter LLaMA model trained with a batch size of 1, LoRA weights occupy only 26 MB, while the memory footprint for the LoRA input gradients is 567 MB. This shows that with batch size 1, the dominant memory requirement comes from activation gradients rather than the adapter weights themselves.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"97d19c42-b378-4f2c-a921-31acbe87701e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:52.775Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"QLoRA 7B fine-tuning RAM requirements batch size 1 quantized","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012UcuSn6U5AmerK4HJdDFiC","content":[{"title":"QLoRA Step-by-Step — Fine-Tune a 7B Model on a Laptop","url":"https://blogs.utilia.dev/qlora-step-by-step-fine-tune-7b-laptop"},{"title":"LLM Fine-Tuning Hardware Requirements: VRAM, GPU","url":"https://llmhardware.io/guides/llm-fine-tuning-hardware-requirements"},{"title":"Evolution of meta's llama models and parameter-efficient fine-tuning of large language models: a survey","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.12178"},{"title":"Fine-tuning LLaMA-7B on ~12GB VRAM with QLoRA, 4-bit quantization · GitHub","url":"https://gist.github.com/Birch-san/57878c4a27cf34f57d3e861865a7d0a2"},{"title":"BEACON: A Unified Behavioral-Tactical Framework for Explainable Cybercrime Analysis with Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.06555"},{"title":"Mistral 7B: QLoRA Fine-tuning + 4-bit (Q4/NF4/INT4) VRAM Usage","url":"https://kaitchup.substack.com/p/mistral-7b-recipes-for-fine-tuning"},{"title":"ShareLoRA: Parameter Efficient and Robust Large Language Model Fine-tuning via Shared Low-Rank Adaptation","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.10785"},{"title":"LQ-LoRA: Low-rank Plus Quantized Matrix Decomposition for Efficient   Language Model Finetuning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2311.12023"},{"title":"Token-wise Influential Training Data Retrieval for Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2405.11724"},{"title":"Abstractive summarization from Audio Transcription","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2408.04639"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about QLoRA 7B fine-tuning RAM requirements with batch size 1 and quantization:\n\n## Memory Requirements\n\nA 7B model needs approximately 12 GB VRAM with QLoRA. More specifically, one user reported requiring 11,181 MiB when training on sequence lengths of around 337 tokens, and this can be reduced down to about 10.9GB with memory optimization.\n\n## How QLoRA Achieves These Requirements\n\nQLoRA enables developers to fine-tune models like Llama 2 7B on laptops with as little as 16GB of VRAM by combining quantization with LoRA. By quantizing the base model to 4-bit precision while keeping the LoRA adapters in higher precision, QLoRA reduces memory requirements by up to 75% without significantly impacting model quality.\n\n## Memory Breakdown with Batch Size 1\n\nIn a 7 billion parameter LLaMA model trained with a batch size of 1, LoRA weights occupy only 26 MB, while the memory footprint for the LoRA input gradients is 567 MB. This shows that with batch size 1, the dominant memory requirement comes from activation gradients rather than the adapter weights themselves."],"durationSeconds":6.319576833000407,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"11b41cb6-89aa-458c-8973-54469ac51826","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"1962fa69-a2a0-4c9c-9714-b4771745aa88","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01299RZBrSHPj5C58H3pmpZM","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"mlx-lm LoRA fine-tuning 8B model Apple silicon 16GB memory requirements\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"MLX-LM — Grokipedia\",\"url\":\"https://grokipedia.com/page/MLX-LM\"},{\"title\":\"Run and Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac with MLX-LM 2026 | Markaicode\",\"url\":\"https://markaicode.com/run-fine-tune-llms-mac-mlx-lm/\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM\",\"url\":\"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/\"},{\"title\":\"Train Your Own LLM on MacBook: A Fine-tuning Guide with MLX | by Dushyant Mahajan | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@dummahajan/train-your-own-llm-on-macbook-a-15-minute-guide-with-mlx-6c6ed9ad036a\"},{\"title\":\"MLX Apple Silicon AI Dev Stack: Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac\",\"url\":\"https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs Locally Using MLX LM\",\"url\":\"https://dzone.com/articles/fine-tuning-llms-locally-using-mlx-lm-guide\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs with LoRA and MLX-LM | by Joana Levtcheva | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@levchevajoana/fine-tuning-llms-with-lora-and-mlx-lm-c0b143642deb\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about mlx-lm LoRA fine-tuning with 8B models on Apple Silicon with 16GB memory:\n\n## Memory Requirements\n\nFor running 8-billion parameter models, at least 16 GB of unified memory is recommended to accommodate model weights, activations, and caching without significant performance degradation; for example, an 8B parameter model in BF16 precision can require around 17 GB of memory.\n\n## Practical Implementation with 16GB\n\nThe good news is that QLoRA on a 16GB MacBook can fine-tune an 8B model in about an hour. Additionally, on a 16GB M2 MacBook Pro, you can run Mistral 7B at ~40 tokens/sec and fine-tune a LoRA adapter on a custom dataset in under 30 minutes.\n\n## Hardware Compatibility\n\nMLX-LM is designed exclusively for Apple Silicon hardware, specifically M-series chips such as the M1 and later models, leveraging the unified memory architecture for efficient machine learning operations.\n\n## Hyperparameter Recommendations\n\nMore LoRA layers means more trainable parameters and better fine-tune quality, but slower training and higher memory use. Start with 8 for quick experiments, increase to 16–32 for production adapters on 16GB+ machines.\n\n## LoRA vs QLoRA\n\nMLX-LM can fine-tune with QLoRA (quantized base + LoRA) — when you pass a 4-bit quantized model as --model with --train, MLX-LM automatically does QLoRA: the base stays quantized, only the LoRA adapter weights are full precision.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"e6f047af-89b9-426d-971d-eeaa554fbe93","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:54.771Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"mlx-lm LoRA fine-tuning 8B model Apple silicon 16GB memory requirements","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01SYUS32yrPQn56ZgXmWntyp","content":[{"title":"MLX-LM — Grokipedia","url":"https://grokipedia.com/page/MLX-LM"},{"title":"Run and Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac with MLX-LM 2026 | Markaicode","url":"https://markaicode.com/run-fine-tune-llms-mac-mlx-lm/"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM","url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/"},{"title":"Train Your Own LLM on MacBook: A Fine-tuning Guide with MLX | by Dushyant Mahajan | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@dummahajan/train-your-own-llm-on-macbook-a-15-minute-guide-with-mlx-6c6ed9ad036a"},{"title":"MLX Apple Silicon AI Dev Stack: Fine-Tune LLMs on Mac","url":"https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs Locally Using MLX LM","url":"https://dzone.com/articles/fine-tuning-llms-locally-using-mlx-lm-guide"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs with LoRA and MLX-LM | by Joana Levtcheva | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@levchevajoana/fine-tuning-llms-with-lora-and-mlx-lm-c0b143642deb"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about mlx-lm LoRA fine-tuning with 8B models on Apple Silicon with 16GB memory:\n\n## Memory Requirements\n\nFor running 8-billion parameter models, at least 16 GB of unified memory is recommended to accommodate model weights, activations, and caching without significant performance degradation; for example, an 8B parameter model in BF16 precision can require around 17 GB of memory.\n\n## Practical Implementation with 16GB\n\nThe good news is that QLoRA on a 16GB MacBook can fine-tune an 8B model in about an hour. Additionally, on a 16GB M2 MacBook Pro, you can run Mistral 7B at ~40 tokens/sec and fine-tune a LoRA adapter on a custom dataset in under 30 minutes.\n\n## Hardware Compatibility\n\nMLX-LM is designed exclusively for Apple Silicon hardware, specifically M-series chips such as the M1 and later models, leveraging the unified memory architecture for efficient machine learning operations.\n\n## Hyperparameter Recommendations\n\nMore LoRA layers means more trainable parameters and better fine-tune quality, but slower training and higher memory use. Start with 8 for quick experiments, increase to 16–32 for production adapters on 16GB+ machines.\n\n## LoRA vs QLoRA\n\nMLX-LM can fine-tune with QLoRA (quantized base + LoRA) — when you pass a 4-bit quantized model as --model with --train, MLX-LM automatically does QLoRA: the base stays quantized, only the LoRA adapter weights are full precision."],"durationSeconds":8.3242910830006,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1962fa69-a2a0-4c9c-9714-b4771745aa88","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"3150cf24-f13e-40d7-b469-8b426a231e55","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FRyHzchap2XujAMBLnJBxK","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"DeepSeek-R1 distill Qwen 7B 1.5B coding math benchmark distillation effectiveness\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"DeepSeek: R1 Distill Qwen 7B\",\"url\":\"https://openrouter.ai/deepseek/deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b\"},{\"title\":\"DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b\"},{\"title\":\"DeepSeek-R1: Incentivizing Reasoning Capability in LLMs via Reinforcement Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1\"},{\"title\":\"DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B - Model Info, Parameters, Benchmarks - SiliconFlow\\\"\",\"url\":\"https://www.siliconflow.com/models/deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b\"},{\"title\":\"DeepSeek R1 Distilled Models for Local AI: Which Version Fits Your GPU (2026)\",\"url\":\"https://runaihome.com/blog/deepseek-r1-distilled-local-inference-vram-guide-2026/\"},{\"title\":\"DeepSeek-R1: Incentivizing Reasoning Capability in LLMs via Reinforcement Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2501.12948\"},{\"title\":\"deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B · Hugging Face\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B\"},{\"title\":\"deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B · Hugging Face\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B\"},{\"title\":\"DeepSeek-R1: Features, o1 Comparison, Distilled Models & More | DataCamp\",\"url\":\"https://www.datacamp.com/blog/deepseek-r1\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's comprehensive information about DeepSeek-R1 distillation effectiveness across the Qwen 7B and 1.5B models on coding and math benchmarks:\n\n## Model Architecture and Distillation Method\n\nDeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B is a 7 billion parameter dense language model distilled from DeepSeek-R1, with the distillation process transferring advanced reasoning, math, and code capabilities into a smaller architecture based on Qwen2.5-Math-7B. The teacher model generates approximately 800,000 high-quality supervised training samples, with the distillation conducted via simple supervised fine-tuning (SFT) using the Qwen2.5-Math-7B architecture as the backbone.\n\n## Math Benchmark Performance\n\nThe distillation has proven highly effective on mathematical benchmarks:\n\n- The 7B model demonstrates strong performance on mathematical benchmarks (92.8% pass@1 on MATH-500)\n- DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B achieves 55.5% on AIME 2024, surpassing QwQ-32B-Preview\n- The straightforward distillation allows DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B to surpass non-reasoning baselines on mathematical benchmarks, with a model of only 1.5 billion parameters achieving superior performance compared to best closed-source models.\n\n## Coding Performance\n\nOn coding tasks, the 7B model achieves a Codeforces rating of 1189. DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B scores 72.6% on AIME 2024, 94.3% on MATH-500, and 57.2% on LiveCodeBench.\n\n## Distillation Effectiveness\n\nModel performance improves progressively as the parameter size of the student model increases, and the distillation approach yields superior performance compared to reinforcement learning alone when applied to smaller model architectures.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"78278017-186f-449f-b2e5-0e80f25a3688","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:56.563Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"DeepSeek-R1 distill Qwen 7B 1.5B coding math benchmark distillation effectiveness","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01KQUYFLzw6eCtd8PPLDXDoV","content":[{"title":"DeepSeek: R1 Distill Qwen 7B","url":"https://openrouter.ai/deepseek/deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b"},{"title":"DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b"},{"title":"DeepSeek-R1: Incentivizing Reasoning Capability in LLMs via Reinforcement Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1"},{"title":"DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B - Model Info, Parameters, Benchmarks - SiliconFlow\"","url":"https://www.siliconflow.com/models/deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b"},{"title":"DeepSeek R1 Distilled Models for Local AI: Which Version Fits Your GPU (2026)","url":"https://runaihome.com/blog/deepseek-r1-distilled-local-inference-vram-guide-2026/"},{"title":"DeepSeek-R1: Incentivizing Reasoning Capability in LLMs via Reinforcement Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2501.12948"},{"title":"deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B · Hugging Face","url":"https://huggingface.co/deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B"},{"title":"deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B · Hugging Face","url":"https://huggingface.co/deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B"},{"title":"DeepSeek-R1: Features, o1 Comparison, Distilled Models & More | DataCamp","url":"https://www.datacamp.com/blog/deepseek-r1"}]},"Based on the search results, here's comprehensive information about DeepSeek-R1 distillation effectiveness across the Qwen 7B and 1.5B models on coding and math benchmarks:\n\n## Model Architecture and Distillation Method\n\nDeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B is a 7 billion parameter dense language model distilled from DeepSeek-R1, with the distillation process transferring advanced reasoning, math, and code capabilities into a smaller architecture based on Qwen2.5-Math-7B. The teacher model generates approximately 800,000 high-quality supervised training samples, with the distillation conducted via simple supervised fine-tuning (SFT) using the Qwen2.5-Math-7B architecture as the backbone.\n\n## Math Benchmark Performance\n\nThe distillation has proven highly effective on mathematical benchmarks:\n\n- The 7B model demonstrates strong performance on mathematical benchmarks (92.8% pass@1 on MATH-500)\n- DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B achieves 55.5% on AIME 2024, surpassing QwQ-32B-Preview\n- The straightforward distillation allows DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B to surpass non-reasoning baselines on mathematical benchmarks, with a model of only 1.5 billion parameters achieving superior performance compared to best closed-source models.\n\n## Coding Performance\n\nOn coding tasks, the 7B model achieves a Codeforces rating of 1189. DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B scores 72.6% on AIME 2024, 94.3% on MATH-500, and 57.2% on LiveCodeBench.\n\n## Distillation Effectiveness\n\nModel performance improves progressively as the parameter size of the student model increases, and the distillation approach yields superior performance compared to reinforcement learning alone when applied to smaller model architectures."],"durationSeconds":8.749982292000205,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3150cf24-f13e-40d7-b469-8b426a231e55","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"0b2d1b9e-c91d-49ff-8af3-132ca647214b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NG3dv9zC6mgo3kVpXqHDNd","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"TinyZero RLVR RL 1.5B 3B model verifiable rewards countdown reasoning\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Reinforcement Learning with Verified Reward (RLVR)\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/reinforcement-learning-with-verified-reward-rlvr\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - TVAO/tinyzero: Clean, accessible reproduction of DeepSeek R1-Zero · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/TVAO/tinyzero\"},{\"title\":\"Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/reinforcement-learning-with-verifiable-rewards-rlvr\"},{\"title\":\"Reinforcement Learning with Verified Rewards (RLVR)\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/reinforcement-learning-with-verified-rewards-rlvr\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero: Minimal reproduction of DeepSeek R1-Zero · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero\"},{\"title\":\"RL with Verifiable Rewards\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/rl-with-verifiable-rewards-rlvr\"},{\"title\":\"CPMobius: Iterative Coach-Player Reasoning for Data-Free Reinforcement Learning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.02979\"},{\"title\":\"Reassessing the Role of Supervised Fine-Tuning: An Empirical Study in VLM Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.12690\"},{\"title\":\"🧠 Tinyzero: Berkeley Researchers Reproduce Deepseek R1-Zero With Extreme Low-Cost\",\"url\":\"https://www.rohan-paul.com/p/tinyzero-berkeley-researchers-reproduce\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's information about TinyZero and RLVR:\n\n## TinyZero\n\nTinyZero is a reproduction of DeepSeek R1 Zero in countdown and multiplication tasks. Through RL, the 3B base LM develops self-verification and search abilities all on its own. The project demonstrates reproducibility at a scale that a PhD student can reimplement in 1-2 days with a cost of less than $30.\n\nThe reproduction of DeepSeek R1-Zero's capabilities was done with Countdown and multiplication tasks using a smaller 3B Qwen base model and Reinforcement Learning. Notably, their experiments show that even a 1.5B model can learn search and self-verification, improving scores, while a 0.5B model struggles with reasoning.\n\n## RLVR (Reinforcement Learning with Verified Reward)\n\nRLVR is a reinforcement learning paradigm that employs objective, verifiable reward functions—such as rule-based checks—to optimize post-training outputs in large language models. It has demonstrated significant performance gains in domains like mathematics, coding, and medical QA by directly optimizing for correctness using minimal curated examples.\n\nRLVR distinguishes itself from conventional reward learning or reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) by relying on rewards that are determined by programmatic or reference-based verification, not through learned scoring models.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"dc414ef8-2d38-4d07-b202-2d7802202c4d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:56.779Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"TinyZero RLVR RL 1.5B 3B model verifiable rewards countdown reasoning","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01VVMyRagFi4ymrRgaMX8Cqs","content":[{"title":"Reinforcement Learning with Verified Reward (RLVR)","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/reinforcement-learning-with-verified-reward-rlvr"},{"title":"GitHub - TVAO/tinyzero: Clean, accessible reproduction of DeepSeek R1-Zero · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/TVAO/tinyzero"},{"title":"Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/reinforcement-learning-with-verifiable-rewards-rlvr"},{"title":"Reinforcement Learning with Verified Rewards (RLVR)","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/reinforcement-learning-with-verified-rewards-rlvr"},{"title":"GitHub - Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero: Minimal reproduction of DeepSeek R1-Zero · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero"},{"title":"RL with Verifiable Rewards","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/rl-with-verifiable-rewards-rlvr"},{"title":"CPMobius: Iterative Coach-Player Reasoning for Data-Free Reinforcement Learning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2602.02979"},{"title":"Reassessing the Role of Supervised Fine-Tuning: An Empirical Study in VLM Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.12690"},{"title":"🧠 Tinyzero: Berkeley Researchers Reproduce Deepseek R1-Zero With Extreme Low-Cost","url":"https://www.rohan-paul.com/p/tinyzero-berkeley-researchers-reproduce"}]},"Based on the search results, here's information about TinyZero and RLVR:\n\n## TinyZero\n\nTinyZero is a reproduction of DeepSeek R1 Zero in countdown and multiplication tasks. Through RL, the 3B base LM develops self-verification and search abilities all on its own. The project demonstrates reproducibility at a scale that a PhD student can reimplement in 1-2 days with a cost of less than $30.\n\nThe reproduction of DeepSeek R1-Zero's capabilities was done with Countdown and multiplication tasks using a smaller 3B Qwen base model and Reinforcement Learning. Notably, their experiments show that even a 1.5B model can learn search and self-verification, improving scores, while a 0.5B model struggles with reasoning.\n\n## RLVR (Reinforcement Learning with Verified Reward)\n\nRLVR is a reinforcement learning paradigm that employs objective, verifiable reward functions—such as rule-based checks—to optimize post-training outputs in large language models. It has demonstrated significant performance gains in domains like mathematics, coding, and medical QA by directly optimizing for correctness using minimal curated examples.\n\nRLVR distinguishes itself from conventional reward learning or reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) by relying on rewards that are determined by programmatic or reference-based verification, not through learned scoring models."],"durationSeconds":9.502665915999561,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0b2d1b9e-c91d-49ff-8af3-132ca647214b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
