{"parentUuid":"a5608b3b-76c8-409b-8e52-eb434d36f8f0","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01BhCBTKaCW2hWsZXKvxuMNS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01JYrhxywrAqsU7jaY66soU2","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://github.com/Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero","prompt":"What model sizes were used (0.5B, 1.5B, 3B), what hardware (GPUs), cost, and what were the findings about which model sizes can learn reasoning/self-verification via RL? Quote specific numbers and the 0.5B vs 1.5B vs 3B distinction."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1445,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4979,"cache_read_input_tokens":11801,"output_tokens":397,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4979},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1445,"output_tokens":397,"cache_read_input_tokens":11801,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4979,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4979,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG24uKgkYwcQj9igwVVN","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"0b69e44a-6914-4094-9d88-f84b71be2082","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:03.022Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"0b69e44a-6914-4094-9d88-f84b71be2082","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JYrhxywrAqsU7jaY66soU2","type":"tool_result","content":"# TinyZero Model Sizes and Findings\n\n**Model Sizes Tested:**\nThe repository experimented with three model scales: 0.5B, 1.5B, and 3B variants of Qwen2.5.\n\n**Key Finding on Learning Capability:**\nAccording to the documentation, \"For Qwen2.5-0.5B base, we know it fails to learn reasoning.\" In contrast, the repository notes that \"the base model is able to develop sophisticated reasoning skills\" when using 3B+ models.\n\n**Hardware Requirements:**\n- **Single GPU setup:** Supports models up to 1.5B\n- **Multi-GPU setup:** 2 GPUs recommended for 3B+ models (with tensor parallelism size of 2)\n\n**Cost:**\nThe authors state you can \"experience the Aha moment yourself for < $30,\" indicating the entire experiment is achievable at minimal expense.\n\n**Summary:**\nThe critical threshold appears to be between 1.5B and 3B—the smallest model failed to develop reasoning, while 3B models successfully learned self-verification and search abilities through reinforcement learning."}]},"uuid":"a48967f4-2a8d-4a0f-9289-a9d9e600eb2a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:09.276Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":303695,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# TinyZero Model Sizes and Findings\n\n**Model Sizes Tested:**\nThe repository experimented with three model scales: 0.5B, 1.5B, and 3B variants of Qwen2.5.\n\n**Key Finding on Learning Capability:**\nAccording to the documentation, \"For Qwen2.5-0.5B base, we know it fails to learn reasoning.\" In contrast, the repository notes that \"the base model is able to develop sophisticated reasoning skills\" when using 3B+ models.\n\n**Hardware Requirements:**\n- **Single GPU setup:** Supports models up to 1.5B\n- **Multi-GPU setup:** 2 GPUs recommended for 3B+ models (with tensor parallelism size of 2)\n\n**Cost:**\nThe authors state you can \"experience the Aha moment yourself for < $30,\" indicating the entire experiment is achievable at minimal expense.\n\n**Summary:**\nThe critical threshold appears to be between 1.5B and 3B—the smallest model failed to develop reasoning, while 3B models successfully learned self-verification and search abilities through reinforcement learning.","durationMs":5450,"url":"https://github.com/Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0b69e44a-6914-4094-9d88-f84b71be2082","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"a5608b3b-76c8-409b-8e52-eb434d36f8f0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_013hUcSjwVECH73J2iqyUisJ","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"RLVR small base model elicits existing capability not new pass@k limits 7B Qwen\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"RLVR Doesn't Expand LLM Reasoning, Just Optimizes Sampling: New Study - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/aimodels-fyi/rlvr-doesnt-expand-llm-reasoning-just-optimizes-sampling-new-study-5fc4\"},{\"title\":\"RLVR's Impact on LLM Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2504.13837\"},{\"title\":\"Papers Explained 354: Does RL Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model? | by Ritvik Rastogi | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://ritvik19.medium.com/papers-explained-354-does-rl-incentivize-reasoning-capacity-in-llms-beyond-the-base-model-77ae394a5054\"},{\"title\":\"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model? | AI Research Paper Details\",\"url\":\"https://www.aimodels.fyi/papers/arxiv/does-reinforcement-learning-really-incentivize-reasoning-capacity\"},{\"title\":\"Limit of RLVR\",\"url\":\"https://limit-of-rlvr.github.io/\"},{\"title\":\"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model? | by Eleventh Hour Enthusiast | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@EleventhHourEnthusiast/does-reinforcement-learning-really-incentivize-reasoning-capacity-in-llms-beyond-the-base-model-b98412ebabee\"},{\"title\":\"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.13837\"},{\"title\":\"Reinforcement Learning vs. Distillation: Understanding Accuracy and Capability in LLM Reasoning\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.14216\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I can provide you with information about this research:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nThe research finds that the current RLVR training setup does not elicit fundamentally new reasoning patterns. More specifically:\n\n**Performance at Different k Values:**\nWhile RLVR-trained models outperform their base models at small k (e.g., k = 1), the base models achieve a higher pass@k score when k is large.\n\n**Broader Problem Coverage:**\nBase models have a broader coverage of solvable problems than their RL-enhanced versions, even if they are less efficient at sampling the correct answer initially.\n\n**Core Insight:**\nCurrent RLVR methods (specifically those using binary 0/1 rewards) do not appear to teach models fundamentally new reasoning abilities. Instead, they primarily amplify reasoning capabilities that already exist within the base model.\n\n**Specific Example with 7B Models:**\nOn LiveCodeBench, the original Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct model achieves a pass@1 score of 23.8%, while the RLVR-trained model reaches 28.1%. However, at k=128, approximately 50% of coding problems were solved by the original model compared to only 42.8% by the RLVR model.\n\nThis research demonstrates that RLVR improves single-sample accuracy but comes at the cost of reduced exploration diversity compared to base models.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"1b0fe1db-cb71-456b-93e8-d64b7a6e24c9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:09.684Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"RLVR small base model elicits existing capability not new pass@k limits 7B Qwen","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012uo3jgHDE5nazSBaXHEoTq","content":[{"title":"RLVR Doesn't Expand LLM Reasoning, Just Optimizes Sampling: New Study - DEV Community","url":"https://dev.to/aimodels-fyi/rlvr-doesnt-expand-llm-reasoning-just-optimizes-sampling-new-study-5fc4"},{"title":"RLVR's Impact on LLM Reasoning","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/papers/2504.13837"},{"title":"Papers Explained 354: Does RL Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model? | by Ritvik Rastogi | Medium","url":"https://ritvik19.medium.com/papers-explained-354-does-rl-incentivize-reasoning-capacity-in-llms-beyond-the-base-model-77ae394a5054"},{"title":"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model? | AI Research Paper Details","url":"https://www.aimodels.fyi/papers/arxiv/does-reinforcement-learning-really-incentivize-reasoning-capacity"},{"title":"Limit of RLVR","url":"https://limit-of-rlvr.github.io/"},{"title":"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model? | by Eleventh Hour Enthusiast | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@EleventhHourEnthusiast/does-reinforcement-learning-really-incentivize-reasoning-capacity-in-llms-beyond-the-base-model-b98412ebabee"},{"title":"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.13837"},{"title":"Reinforcement Learning vs. Distillation: Understanding Accuracy and Capability in LLM Reasoning","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.14216"}]},"Based on the search results, I can provide you with information about this research:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nThe research finds that the current RLVR training setup does not elicit fundamentally new reasoning patterns. More specifically:\n\n**Performance at Different k Values:**\nWhile RLVR-trained models outperform their base models at small k (e.g., k = 1), the base models achieve a higher pass@k score when k is large.\n\n**Broader Problem Coverage:**\nBase models have a broader coverage of solvable problems than their RL-enhanced versions, even if they are less efficient at sampling the correct answer initially.\n\n**Core Insight:**\nCurrent RLVR methods (specifically those using binary 0/1 rewards) do not appear to teach models fundamentally new reasoning abilities. Instead, they primarily amplify reasoning capabilities that already exist within the base model.\n\n**Specific Example with 7B Models:**\nOn LiveCodeBench, the original Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct model achieves a pass@1 score of 23.8%, while the RLVR-trained model reaches 28.1%. However, at k=128, approximately 50% of coding problems were solved by the original model compared to only 42.8% by the RLVR model.\n\nThis research demonstrates that RLVR improves single-sample accuracy but comes at the cost of reduced exploration diversity compared to base models."],"durationSeconds":7.847546000000089,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a5608b3b-76c8-409b-8e52-eb434d36f8f0","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"42829b12-fa85-4546-9cca-2e1fa1e115be","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K8VHqjTCHJEShNNgRZpdpU","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"self-training self-rewarding small model coding capability plateau model collapse self-distillation limits\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Self-Correcting Code Generation Using Small Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.23060\"},{\"title\":\"A Survey of On-Policy Distillation for Large Language Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.00626\"},{\"title\":\"Self distillation. Why a model can sometimes learn more… | by Jaideep Ray | Better ML | Apr, 2026 | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/better-ml/self-distillation-20a42c0be415\"},{\"title\":\"Reinforcement Learning via Self-Distillation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.20802v1\"},{\"title\":\"Pre-training under infinite compute\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.14786\"},{\"title\":\"SRT: Can Large Reasoning Models Self-Train?\",\"url\":\"https://self-rewarding-llm-training.github.io/\"},{\"title\":\"Think, Prune, Train, Improve: Scaling Reasoning Without Scaling Models\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.18116v1\"},{\"title\":\"Embarrassingly Simple Self-Distillation Improves Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiviq.substack.com/p/embarrassingly-simple-self-distillation\"},{\"title\":\"Embarrassingly Simple Self-Distillation Improves Code Generation\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.01193v1\"}]\n\nI found several relevant papers and resources on self-training, self-rewarding, and self-distillation approaches for small language models with their limitations. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Self-Training and Model Collapse\n\nProlonged RL with self-reward leads to reward hacking where models learn to maximize training reward, resulting in sudden performance collapse. More specifically, the model learns to maximize self-assigned rewards by producing consistent but incorrect answers, where the optimal policy degenerates to producing the same answer regardless of input, maximizing reward artificially.\n\n## Self-Distillation Saturation\n\nA critical theoretical bottleneck in self-distillation is the rapid onset of policy saturation, where after a few iterations of SPIN or OPSD, empirical observations universally note a plateau or severe degradation. Because the student optimizes against a target sharing its own inductive biases and architectural limitations, the hypothesis space progressively collapses.\n\n## Small Model-Specific Issues\n\nFor small language models specifically, introducing certain KL-divergence regularization terms leads to training collapse for SLMs, as shown by reward converging to zero. Training collapse arises from the limited self-correction ability of SLMs.\n\n## Mitigation Strategies\n\nUnfiltered recursive fine-tuning can degrade model performance, but correctness-based pruning stabilizes training, preserving knowledge while enhancing reasoning. Additionally, by mixing together real tokens and synthetic tokens, one can avoid collapse and train a student that vastly outperforms its teacher.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"689b3132-d789-4e6b-82b6-f977f2553048","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:12.542Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"self-training self-rewarding small model coding capability plateau model collapse self-distillation limits","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01BCp2BTo2y6DJfXsGK1S6bz","content":[{"title":"Self-Correcting Code Generation Using Small Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.23060"},{"title":"A Survey of On-Policy Distillation for Large Language Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2604.00626"},{"title":"Self distillation. Why a model can sometimes learn more… | by Jaideep Ray | Better ML | Apr, 2026 | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/better-ml/self-distillation-20a42c0be415"},{"title":"Reinforcement Learning via Self-Distillation","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2601.20802v1"},{"title":"Pre-training under infinite compute","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.14786"},{"title":"SRT: Can Large Reasoning Models Self-Train?","url":"https://self-rewarding-llm-training.github.io/"},{"title":"Think, Prune, Train, Improve: Scaling Reasoning Without Scaling Models","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.18116v1"},{"title":"Embarrassingly Simple Self-Distillation Improves Code Generation","url":"https://arxiviq.substack.com/p/embarrassingly-simple-self-distillation"},{"title":"Embarrassingly Simple Self-Distillation Improves Code Generation","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2604.01193v1"}]},"I found several relevant papers and resources on self-training, self-rewarding, and self-distillation approaches for small language models with their limitations. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Self-Training and Model Collapse\n\nProlonged RL with self-reward leads to reward hacking where models learn to maximize training reward, resulting in sudden performance collapse. More specifically, the model learns to maximize self-assigned rewards by producing consistent but incorrect answers, where the optimal policy degenerates to producing the same answer regardless of input, maximizing reward artificially.\n\n## Self-Distillation Saturation\n\nA critical theoretical bottleneck in self-distillation is the rapid onset of policy saturation, where after a few iterations of SPIN or OPSD, empirical observations universally note a plateau or severe degradation. Because the student optimizes against a target sharing its own inductive biases and architectural limitations, the hypothesis space progressively collapses.\n\n## Small Model-Specific Issues\n\nFor small language models specifically, introducing certain KL-divergence regularization terms leads to training collapse for SLMs, as shown by reward converging to zero. Training collapse arises from the limited self-correction ability of SLMs.\n\n## Mitigation Strategies\n\nUnfiltered recursive fine-tuning can degrade model performance, but correctness-based pruning stabilizes training, preserving knowledge while enhancing reasoning. Additionally, by mixing together real tokens and synthetic tokens, one can avoid collapse and train a student that vastly outperforms its teacher."],"durationSeconds":11.757073541998864,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"42829b12-fa85-4546-9cca-2e1fa1e115be","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
