{"parentUuid":"57bb97f0-43af-4ce5-b095-1075eaec3678","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_017Yoh9p5jRi5TWxsVQq589v","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VFY4jXALZD82xdFvemfPXe","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md","prompt":"What are the documented memory requirements for LoRA/QLoRA fine-tuning of 7B/8B models? Look for specific RAM/GB numbers, batch size recommendations, gradient checkpointing, quantized model usage, and any guidance for memory-limited (e.g. 16GB or 32GB) machines. Quote specifics."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1657,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2954,"cache_read_input_tokens":16780,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2954,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2655qjf5H8SS4A2zVq","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"e8c12593-e4c9-43f1-9d5a-a202c1f14fb2","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:19.506Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"e8c12593-e4c9-43f1-9d5a-a202c1f14fb2","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_017Yoh9p5jRi5TWxsVQq589v","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01X3nmkBdiEJ9Ajty8vMCdE7","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1","prompt":"Find the section comparing distillation vs reinforcement learning on small models. Quote the specific finding: did distilling from R1 into small models (e.g. Qwen-32B/7B) outperform running large-scale RL directly on those small models? Quote the exact numbers/conclusion about distillation vs RL on small dense models."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1657,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2954,"cache_read_input_tokens":16780,"output_tokens":454,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2954},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1657,"output_tokens":454,"cache_read_input_tokens":16780,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2954,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2954,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2655qjf5H8SS4A2zVq","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"3d28dd5d-1673-485e-8a87-d0f91a3793f9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:21.599Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"3d28dd5d-1673-485e-8a87-d0f91a3793f9","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01X3nmkBdiEJ9Ajty8vMCdE7","type":"tool_result","content":"# Distillation vs Reinforcement Learning on Small Models\n\nAccording to Section 4.1 of the paper, distillation significantly outperformed direct RL training on smaller models.\n\n**Key Finding:**\n\nThe authors compared DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B (distilled from R1) against DeepSeek-R1-Zero-Qwen-32B (RL trained directly on Qwen-32B). The results showed:\n\n\"the 32B base model, after large-scale RL training, achieves performance on par with QwQ-32B-Preview. However, DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B, which is distilled from DeepSeek-R1, performs significantly better than DeepSeek-R1-Zero-Qwen-32B across all benchmarks.\"\n\n**Specific Numbers (Table 6):**\n- AIME 2024: Distilled 72.6% vs RL-trained 47.0%\n- MATH-500: Distilled 83.3% vs RL-trained 60.0%\n- GPQA Diamond: Distilled 94.3% vs RL-trained 91.6%\n\n**Conclusion:** The authors concluded that \"distilling more powerful models into smaller ones yields excellent results, whereas smaller models relying on large-scale RL require enormous computational power and may not achieve distillation's performance.\""}]},"uuid":"fc8bfc20-e9ba-488b-b678-44ce3fa4d92d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:27.501Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":225172,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Distillation vs Reinforcement Learning on Small Models\n\nAccording to Section 4.1 of the paper, distillation significantly outperformed direct RL training on smaller models.\n\n**Key Finding:**\n\nThe authors compared DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B (distilled from R1) against DeepSeek-R1-Zero-Qwen-32B (RL trained directly on Qwen-32B). The results showed:\n\n\"the 32B base model, after large-scale RL training, achieves performance on par with QwQ-32B-Preview. However, DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B, which is distilled from DeepSeek-R1, performs significantly better than DeepSeek-R1-Zero-Qwen-32B across all benchmarks.\"\n\n**Specific Numbers (Table 6):**\n- AIME 2024: Distilled 72.6% vs RL-trained 47.0%\n- MATH-500: Distilled 83.3% vs RL-trained 60.0%\n- GPQA Diamond: Distilled 94.3% vs RL-trained 91.6%\n\n**Conclusion:** The authors concluded that \"distilling more powerful models into smaller ones yields excellent results, whereas smaller models relying on large-scale RL require enormous computational power and may not achieve distillation's performance.\"","durationMs":5648,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3d28dd5d-1673-485e-8a87-d0f91a3793f9","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"fc8bfc20-e9ba-488b-b678-44ce3fa4d92d","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015qauQTnKVqky1K2sLQRUyd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have strong primary-source coverage. Let me do one more check on real-world MLX 16GB LoRA experiences to cross-check the \"fits in 16GB\" claim with a concrete account."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3078,"cache_read_input_tokens":19734,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3078,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG27AgTujV99ZNQwTEgh","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"875d38e1-f9ba-42e7-9d2b-3a41cbd5df91","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:30.182Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"875d38e1-f9ba-42e7-9d2b-3a41cbd5df91","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015qauQTnKVqky1K2sLQRUyd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0165tFkBCjztQWgXdbWVgEy7","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"MLX LoRA fine-tune 16GB MacBook 8B model out of memory swap experience batch size 1 grad checkpoint"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3078,"cache_read_input_tokens":19734,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3078,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG27AgTujV99ZNQwTEgh","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"c802df34-9856-4ce1-97ec-c8024f51fffa","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:30.755Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"c802df34-9856-4ce1-97ec-c8024f51fffa","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0165tFkBCjztQWgXdbWVgEy7","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"MLX LoRA fine-tune 16GB MacBook 8B model out of memory swap experience batch size 1 grad checkpoint\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[BUG] Memory overflow when lora fine-tuning meta-llama/Meta-Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct · Issue #1406 · ml-explore/mlx\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/1406\"},{\"title\":\"How to Fine-Tune a Small LLM on a Laptop: Hardware Guide\",\"url\":\"https://www.laptophub.net/how-to-fine-tune-small-llm-on-laptop/\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM\",\"url\":\"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning LLMs on Mac: Complete MLX Framework Guide\",\"url\":\"https://randalscottking.com/fine-tuning-llms-mac-mlx-framework/\"},{\"title\":\"The Hitchhiker’s Guide to Fine Tune LLMs on a Mac | by Rhitam Deb | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@neevdeb26/the-hitchhikers-guide-to-fine-tune-llms-on-a-mac-85174455457a\"},{\"title\":\"mlx-lm/mlx_lm/LORA.md at main · ml-explore/mlx-lm\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md\"},{\"title\":\"Train Your Own LLM on MacBook: A Fine-tuning Guide with MLX | by Dushyant Mahajan | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@dummahajan/train-your-own-llm-on-macbook-a-15-minute-guide-with-mlx-6c6ed9ad036a\"},{\"title\":\"Potential memory leak during Llama 3 8b model fine-tuning with LoRA · Issue #738 · ml-explore/mlx-examples\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-examples/issues/738\"},{\"title\":\"Fine-Tuning on a MacBook: MLX, 3 Minutes, 90 Examples, and a Model That Actually Works | by florinelchis | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://florinelchis.medium.com/fine-tuning-on-a-macbook-mlx-3-minutes-90-examples-and-a-model-that-actually-works-7de0547da347\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about MLX LoRA fine-tuning on a 16GB MacBook with 8B models:\n\n## Memory Constraints with 16GB MacBooks\n\nQLoRA on a 16GB MacBook fine-tunes an 8B model in about an hour, but this comes with significant caveats. 7B models show marginal feasibility with \"batch=1, seq=512\" configuration and have \"OOM risk\" on 16GB machines.\n\n## Out-of-Memory and Swap Issues\n\nWhen checking Activity Monitor for memory pressure, yellow/red indicates the system is swapping, which destroys training speed. This is critical to monitor when pushing the limits of your hardware.\n\n## Recommended Mitigation Strategies\n\nIf you encounter out-of-memory errors, the solutions include:\n\n1. **Batch Size**: Reduce batch-size to 1, lower lora-layers to 4 or 6, use a smaller model, or close other applications\n\n2. **Gradient Checkpointing**: --grad-checkpoint saves memory but adds ~30% training time. Only use it if you need to\n\n3. **Quantization**: Use MLX-format quantized versions from the mlx-community organization on HuggingFace, or quantize yourself, and point mlx_lm.lora at the quantized model\n\n4. **Sequence Length**: Make sure examples are under 3,500 tokens each. Very long sequences slow training and eat memory\n\nThe reality is that 3B models are the \"sweet spot\" for 16GB machines, with 8B models representing a marginal configuration that requires careful tuning and risks swapping to disk.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"2034d3ef-04b8-4d4a-8889-df6e25c27941","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:43.814Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"MLX LoRA fine-tune 16GB MacBook 8B model out of memory swap experience batch size 1 grad checkpoint","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Ut3Fwn9JkUV1pmXPA2dRZV","content":[{"title":"[BUG] Memory overflow when lora fine-tuning meta-llama/Meta-Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct · Issue #1406 · ml-explore/mlx","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/1406"},{"title":"How to Fine-Tune a Small LLM on a Laptop: Hardware Guide","url":"https://www.laptophub.net/how-to-fine-tune-small-llm-on-laptop/"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning on Mac: LoRA & QLoRA with MLX | InsiderLLM","url":"https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning LLMs on Mac: Complete MLX Framework Guide","url":"https://randalscottking.com/fine-tuning-llms-mac-mlx-framework/"},{"title":"The Hitchhiker’s Guide to Fine Tune LLMs on a Mac | by Rhitam Deb | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@neevdeb26/the-hitchhikers-guide-to-fine-tune-llms-on-a-mac-85174455457a"},{"title":"mlx-lm/mlx_lm/LORA.md at main · ml-explore/mlx-lm","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md"},{"title":"Train Your Own LLM on MacBook: A Fine-tuning Guide with MLX | by Dushyant Mahajan | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@dummahajan/train-your-own-llm-on-macbook-a-15-minute-guide-with-mlx-6c6ed9ad036a"},{"title":"Potential memory leak during Llama 3 8b model fine-tuning with LoRA · Issue #738 · ml-explore/mlx-examples","url":"https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-examples/issues/738"},{"title":"Fine-Tuning on a MacBook: MLX, 3 Minutes, 90 Examples, and a Model That Actually Works | by florinelchis | Medium","url":"https://florinelchis.medium.com/fine-tuning-on-a-macbook-mlx-3-minutes-90-examples-and-a-model-that-actually-works-7de0547da347"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about MLX LoRA fine-tuning on a 16GB MacBook with 8B models:\n\n## Memory Constraints with 16GB MacBooks\n\nQLoRA on a 16GB MacBook fine-tunes an 8B model in about an hour, but this comes with significant caveats. 7B models show marginal feasibility with \"batch=1, seq=512\" configuration and have \"OOM risk\" on 16GB machines.\n\n## Out-of-Memory and Swap Issues\n\nWhen checking Activity Monitor for memory pressure, yellow/red indicates the system is swapping, which destroys training speed. This is critical to monitor when pushing the limits of your hardware.\n\n## Recommended Mitigation Strategies\n\nIf you encounter out-of-memory errors, the solutions include:\n\n1. **Batch Size**: Reduce batch-size to 1, lower lora-layers to 4 or 6, use a smaller model, or close other applications\n\n2. **Gradient Checkpointing**: --grad-checkpoint saves memory but adds ~30% training time. Only use it if you need to\n\n3. **Quantization**: Use MLX-format quantized versions from the mlx-community organization on HuggingFace, or quantize yourself, and point mlx_lm.lora at the quantized model\n\n4. **Sequence Length**: Make sure examples are under 3,500 tokens each. Very long sequences slow training and eat memory\n\nThe reality is that 3B models are the \"sweet spot\" for 16GB machines, with 8B models representing a marginal configuration that requires careful tuning and risks swapping to disk."],"durationSeconds":12.407858582999557,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c802df34-9856-4ce1-97ec-c8024f51fffa","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"2034d3ef-04b8-4d4a-8889-df6e25c27941","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aed8b63927090d2d9","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_014x3t1Q8UdwXaouEbJpnhYV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have enough cross-checked evidence. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Findings: On-device 8B training + self-training/RLVR for small models\n\n## A. LoRA/QLoRA fine-tuning of 7-8B on 16 GB Apple silicon\n\n**CLAIM 1 — QLoRA on an 8B model fits and trains on a 16 GB Mac, but only as a marginal config requiring careful tuning.**\n- Detail: Multiple guides say \"QLoRA on a 16GB MacBook can fine-tune an 8B model in about an hour,\" but qualify that 7-8B is the *edge* of feasibility — \"marginal feasibility with batch=1, seq=512\" and \"OOM risk on 16GB.\" The stated \"sweet spot\" for 16 GB is **3B models**, not 8B.\n- Source: https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/ ; https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026\n\n**CLAIM 2 — Official mlx-lm docs give a 7B reference config of batch-size 1 / 4 layers and demonstrate it on a 32 GB machine, NOT 16 GB.**\n- Detail: The canonical LORA.md example is `mlx_lm.lora --model Mistral-7B --train --batch-size 1 --num-layers 4`, benchmarked at ~250 tok/s on an M1 Max **32GB**. The docs deliberately give **no minimum-RAM figure** — they say \"a machine with a decent amount of memory.\" All official worked examples use 32 GB.\n- Source: https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md\n- **CONFLICT FLAG:** Blog posts assert 16 GB works for 8B; Apple's own docs only demonstrate 32 GB for 7B. The official source is more conservative than the blogs.\n\n**CLAIM 3 — An 8B model in BF16 needs ~17 GB just for weights — i.e. you cannot full-precision fine-tune 8B on 16 GB; the base must be 4-bit quantized (QLoRA).**\n- Detail: \"an 8B parameter model in BF16 precision can require around 17 GB.\" Hence on 16 GB you must run QLoRA (4-bit quantized base), which cuts memory ~75%.\n- Source: https://grokipedia.com/page/MLX-LM ; QLoRA reduction figure: https://blogs.utilia.dev/qlora-step-by-step-fine-tune-7b-laptop\n\n**CLAIM 4 — The memory levers that make 8B fit on 16 GB: 4-bit quantized base + batch-size 1 + reduce LoRA layers to 4-8 + `--grad-checkpoint` + short sequences (<~3,500 tokens).**\n- Detail: `--grad-checkpoint` trades compute for memory at roughly **+30% training time**. Watching Activity Monitor for yellow/red memory pressure (swap) is advised because swap \"destroys training speed.\"\n- Source: https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md ; https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/\n\n**CLAIM 5 — Real OOM reports exist for Llama-3.1-8B LoRA under MLX (so 16 GB headroom is genuinely thin).**\n- Detail: Open GitHub issues report \"Memory overflow when lora fine-tuning Meta-Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct\" and a suspected \"memory leak during Llama 3 8b LoRA fine-tuning.\"\n- Source: https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/1406 ; https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-examples/issues/738\n\n**CLAIM 6 — Reference QLoRA-7B VRAM/RAM footprint on non-Apple hardware is ~11-12 GB (consistent with 16 GB being tight-but-feasible).**\n- Detail: \"~12 GB VRAM with QLoRA\"; one report of 11,181 MiB at seq~337 tokens, reducible to ~10.9 GB. With batch size 1, dominant cost is activation/input gradients (~567 MB) not adapter weights (~26 MB) — so sequence length and layer count drive memory.\n- Source: https://blogs.utilia.dev/qlora-step-by-step-fine-tune-7b-laptop ; https://gist.github.com/Birch-san/57878c4a27cf34f57d3e861865a7d0a2 ; arXiv PEFT survey https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.12178\n\n**Speed datapoint:** 7B LoRA adapter \"in under 30 minutes\" on a 16 GB M2 MBP per one blog (treat as optimistic/small-dataset). Source: https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026\n\n---\n\n## B. RLVR on small models (does it work for coding/math?)\n\n**CLAIM 7 — RL with verifiable rewards works on 3B and even 1.5B, but ~0.5B fails to learn reasoning. The threshold is between 1.5B and 3B.**\n- Detail: TinyZero (Jiayi Pan, Berkeley): a 3B Qwen2.5 base \"develops self-verification and search abilities on its own\" via RL on Countdown/multiplication. \"Even a 1.5B model can learn search and self-verification\"; \"Qwen2.5-0.5B base… fails to learn reasoning.\" Reproducible for **< $30**.\n- Source: https://github.com/Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero ; https://www.rohan-paul.com/p/tinyzero-berkeley-researchers-reproduce\n- Hardware note: single GPU handles ≤1.5B; 3B+ wants 2 GPUs (tensor-parallel 2). This is datacenter GPU, not the Mac.\n\n**CLAIM 8 — RLVR is the right paradigm where reward = a programmatic check (tests pass) — proven gains in math, coding, medical QA from minimal curated data.**\n- Detail: RLVR uses \"objective, verifiable reward functions—rule-based checks\"; distinguished from RLHF by not using a learned reward model.\n- Source: https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/reinforcement-learning-with-verifiable-rewards-rlvr\n\n**CLAIM 9 — CRITICAL CAVEAT: RLVR mostly *sharpens sampling of capabilities the base already has*; it does NOT add fundamentally new reasoning, and can shrink problem coverage.**\n- Detail: On LiveCodeBench, Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct base = 23.8% pass@1; RLVR-trained = 28.1% pass@1 (RL wins at k=1). But at **k=128, base solves ~50% of coding problems vs only 42.8% for the RLVR model** — the base has broader coverage. RLVR trades exploration diversity for single-sample accuracy.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.13837 (\"Does RL Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity Beyond the Base Model?\") ; https://limit-of-rlvr.github.io/\n- **Implication for Yogi:** RLVR on qwen3:8b can lift pass@1 on tasks the base can already sometimes solve, but won't conjure capabilities the 8B base lacks. This is a real ceiling, not a tuning problem.\n\n---\n\n## C. Self-training / self-rewarding / self-distillation (does it lift or collapse?)\n\n**CLAIM 10 — Self-rewarding RL collapses: the model reward-hacks, degenerating to producing the same answer regardless of input to max self-assigned reward.**\n- Detail: \"Prolonged RL with self-reward leads to reward hacking… sudden performance collapse… optimal policy degenerates to producing the same answer regardless of input.\" SRT study confirms large reasoning models self-training eventually collapse.\n- Source: https://self-rewarding-llm-training.github.io/ (SRT: \"Can Large Reasoning Models Self-Train?\")\n\n**CLAIM 11 — Self-distillation saturates fast: a few iterations of SPIN/OPSD plateau or degrade because the student shares the teacher's own inductive biases (hypothesis space collapses).**\n- Detail: \"rapid onset of policy saturation… after a few iterations… universally note a plateau or severe degradation.\"\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2601.20802v1 (Reinforcement Learning via Self-Distillation)\n\n**CLAIM 12 — Small models are especially collapse-prone; mitigation = correctness-based pruning (verifiable filter) and mixing real + synthetic tokens.**\n- Detail: \"training collapse arises from the limited self-correction ability of SLMs.\" But \"correctness-based pruning stabilizes training, preserving knowledge while enhancing reasoning\" (Think-Prune-Train), and \"mixing real tokens and synthetic tokens\" avoids collapse and can beat the teacher.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2504.18116v1 (Think, Prune, Train, Improve) ; https://arxiv.org/html/2604.01193v1 (self-distillation for code)\n- **Implication:** Self-training only sustains improvement when gated by a *verifiable* correctness filter (tests pass) — i.e. it must be RLVR-style, not self-reward-style. Yogi's \"tests pass\" reward is exactly the stabilizing signal these papers say you need.\n\n---\n\n## D. Distillation from a stronger teacher (most reliable lever)\n\n**CLAIM 13 — Distilling a strong teacher into a small student via plain SFT is highly effective and BEATS large-scale RL on small models.**\n- Detail (DeepSeek-R1 paper, Section 4.1 / Table 6): DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B vs DeepSeek-R1-Zero-Qwen-32B (RL directly on 32B): **AIME 72.6% vs 47.0%; MATH-500 83.3%? (see note) vs 60.0%; GPQA 94.3% vs 91.6%.** Conclusion verbatim: \"distilling more powerful models into smaller ones yields excellent results, whereas smaller models relying on large-scale RL require enormous computational power and may not achieve distillation's performance.\"\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1\n- Note/conflict: the WebFetch returned MATH-500 distilled as 83.3% in the RL-comparison table, while the standard published R1-Distill-Qwen-32B MATH-500 figure is 94.3%. Treat the exact MATH-500 distilled value as needing a direct table check; the *direction* (distill >> RL on small models) is unambiguous.\n\n**CLAIM 14 — Distillation transfers coding+math into small dense students via ~800K SFT samples; quality scales with student size.**\n- Detail: R1 teacher generated ~800,000 SFT samples. R1-Distill-Qwen-7B: 92.8% MATH-500, 55.5% AIME 2024 (beats QwQ-32B-Preview), Codeforces rating 1189. \"Model performance improves progressively as student parameter size increases.\"\n- Source: https://huggingface.co/deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B ; https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1 ; https://www.siliconflow.com/models/deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line / conflicts summary\n\n1. **8B LoRA on 16 GB:** technically possible only as QLoRA (4-bit base) + batch 1 + ≤8 layers + grad-checkpoint + short seqs, and it's genuinely marginal (real OOM reports). **Conflict:** blogs say \"fits, ~1 hr\"; Apple's own docs only demonstrate 32 GB for 7B and quote no 16 GB number. The conservative read: **3B is the comfortable on-device sweet spot for 16 GB; 8B is at the OOM cliff.**\n2. **RLVR works on ≥1.5-3B** with a verifiable (tests-pass) reward, but mainly sharpens existing ability and can *reduce* pass@k coverage — a real ceiling.\n3. **Pure self-reward self-training collapses;** it only sustains gains when gated by a verifiable correctness filter (then it's effectively RLVR).\n4. **Distillation from a stronger teacher (Claude → small student) is the most reliable capability lift and beats small-model RL** per the DeepSeek-R1 paper — directly relevant to Yogi's \"frontier teacher = Claude Code, student = qwen3:8b\" design.\n\nCaveats on sourcing: several memory/time figures come from third-party blogs (utilia, insiderllm, buildmvpfast, grokipedia) and should be treated as indicative, not guaranteed; the load-bearing primary sources are the mlx-lm LORA.md, the DeepSeek-R1 arXiv paper, the Limit-of-RLVR paper, TinyZero's repo, and the SRT/Think-Prune-Train papers."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1602,"cache_read_input_tokens":22812,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1602,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG28NSg33z8ZY9sUewx3","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"eb27433f-363c-4a01-901e-7797c8e6ef82","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:41.011Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
